I see no reason why exabgp (or any other BGP implementation) should waste time on semantics of the flowspec (or most of the other bits and pieces, flags, attributes, communities, ...). This is something the user should take care of. (I think you really do not want to put any semantics into this, then we may start arguing if a flow containing icmp-codes and tcp-flags at the same time will make sense since such a flow will never match any packet).

However, in our case we are actually doing something meaningfull and intercepting flow-routes between Juniper and Arbor. Both implementations do not put any restrictions what so ever on the types that support this "numeric-string" operator (ports, protocol, icmp-type, icmp-code, length). So, when we receive such a configuration from Arbor or Juniper (ie. icmp-type 1-100) we end up iterating thru 1,2,3,4,5, ... 100 (and even this configuration is not supported since only "names" are currently allowed).

Example (from Juniper config):
```
{master}[edit routing-options flow route BLA]
cl@R06.FLE.xxx# show    
match {
    protocol 1-10;
    icmp-type 20-30;
    icmp-code [ 1-5 20-30 ];
}
```

