Regarding the items issue you discussed above, after thinking about it for a while, we decided we are going to leave the code as-is. Including `None` for empty slots just requires the user to make another check to see if the item is `None`, which is, for 95+% of use cases, just an unnecessary hassle. It will require code like this: `items = [item for item in items if item is not None]` as a precursor to doing almost anything with items, and that's just a pain.  This is one of the rare cases were we are okay sacrificing "perfect" data, in part because it improves the user experience so much for essentially everybody (including you since you said you don't actually use the empty slots for anything). Technically, the empty item slots can still be identified using the underlying data that is accessible via the `.to_dict()` method, so if worst comes to worst, someone can just use that.

